    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2-ue",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error is scoped out for this assessment because the CFD simulations are executed exclusively by the original model development team under a controlled simulation protocol with mandatory peer review of all pre-processing inputs and solver settings prior to execution. The institutional QMS requires a two-person sign-off on boundary condition specification and mesh quality checks, eliminating the class of user-introduced errors that this factor targets. Residual procedural risk is captured under the Software Quality Assurance factor. Re-scoping would be required if the model were transferred to a third-party operator."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2-ts",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test samples is scoped out because the validation experiments use a well-characterised blood analog fluid (glycerin-water at 37°C) rather than biological blood samples. Sample-to-sample biological variability — the primary concern addressed by this factor — is not present in the blood analog, and the fluid properties are controlled to within ±1% of target values through gravimetric preparation. The decision to use a blood analog is consistent with FDA guidance for in-vitro hemolysis testing of VADs and is documented in the test protocol. This scoping decision is bounded: if future COU revisions require validation against whole-blood experiments, this factor must be re-activated."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2-eip",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters is scoped out because the validation experiments were conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump CAD geometry used in the CFD model, with no geometric scaling or simplification applied. Dimensional inspection (CMM, ±0.05 mm) confirmed that all wetted-surface dimensions of the physical test article match the computational geometry within manufacturing tolerances. Because there is no geometry transformation between the validation domain and the COU domain, the parameter-equivalency mapping that this factor evaluates is trivially satisfied and does not require a separate credibility gradation assessment."
    }
